ban there was much discussion
of the President's proposal

00:11:06.065 --> 00:11:08.434
during the campaign
that all Muslims

00:11:08.434 --> 00:11:10.436
be barred from entering the U.S.

00:11:11.103 --> 00:11:13.806
And it was noted during those
arguments that the President

00:11:13.806 --> 00:11:15.775
has never actually
disavowed that proposal.

00:11:16.342 --> 00:11:18.744
And it was also noted that
he had not made those comments

00:11:18.744 --> 00:11:20.346
since being sworn
in as President.

00:11:20.846 --> 00:11:23.416
So, I wanted to ask,
does the White House disavow

00:11:23.416 --> 00:11:25.818
that campaign proposal,

00:11:25.818 --> 00:11:27.386
or does it stand by it?

00:11:27.386 --> 00:11:29.121
Ms. Sanders: The
administration's top priority

00:11:29.121 --> 00:11:32.391
is to ensure the safety and
security of the American people.

00:11:32.391 --> 00:11:33.793
For that reason,

00:11:33.793 --> 00:11:35.461
the administration
has put in place enhanced

00:11:35.461 --> 00:11:38.197
global security measures
to improve screening

00:11:38.197 --> 00:11:39.465
and vetting capabilities

00:11:39.465 --> 00:11:41.567
and share information.
It's working.

00:11:41.567 --> 00:11:43.369
There's been
significant improvements

00:11:43.369 --> 00:11:45.304
in identity management
and information

00:11:45.304 --> 00:11:46.972
sharing with
foreign governments.

00:11:46.972 --> 00:11:48.941
Because of this,
our international partners

00:11:48.941 --> 00:11:51.444
have raised their own
baseline requirements.

00:11:51.444 --> 00:11:54.080
Without the ability to impose
entry restrictions,

00:11:54.080 --> 00:11:55.915
the United States may be forced

00:11:55.915 --> 00:11:58.384
to unsuspectingly
allow dangerous criminals

00:11:58.384 --> 00:12:00.286
or terrorists into the country.

00:12:00.286 --> 00:12:01.821
Additionally, without
the restrictions,

00:12:01.821 --> 00:12:03.355
foreign governments
have little incentive

00:12:03.355 --> 00:12:05.424
to improve their
information-sharing

00:12:05.424 --> 00:12:07.426
and identity-management
practices.

00:12:07.426 --> 00:12:11.397
The focus of this travel ban
has been on safety and security,

00:12:12.031 --> 00:12:14.533
is limited to a small
number of countries,

00:12:15.301 --> 00:12:17.837
and a lot of
Muslim-majority countries

00:12:17.837 --> 00:12:19.839
have the same abilities

00:12:19.839 --> 00:12:21.740
to travel to and
from the United States

00:12:21.740 --> 00:12:23.809
as they did in previous
administrations.

00:12:23.809 --> 00:12:27.213
I think that alone, in action,
answers your question clearly.

00:12:27.913 --> 00:12:28.948
Jim.

00:12:28.948 --> 00:12:31.350
The Press: I just wanted to
follow up on Dr. Ronny Jackson.

00:12:31.350 --> 00:12:33.953
Yesterday, the President
suggested that Dr. Jackson

00:12:33.953 --> 00:12:35.221
does not have the experience

00:12:35.221 --> 00:12:37.556
to run the Department
of Veterans Affairs.

00:12:37.556 --> 00:12:40.192
Is that a fair assessment,
that he lacks that experience?

00:12:40.192 --> 00:12:42.027
Ms. Sanders: That's not what
the President said.

00:12:42.027 --> 00:12:44.663
I think you're taking some
of his words out of context.

00:12:44.663 --> 00:12:46.565
And based on your tweet today --

00:12:46.565 --> 00:12:47.766
The Press: He said experience
is an issue.

00:12:47.766 --> 00:12:48.868
Ms. Sanders: -- I know
you don't appreciate

00:12:48.868 --> 00:12:50.402
when people take your
words out of context.

00:12:50.402 --> 00:12:52.338
So, I'd appreciate if you not
do that to the President.

00:12:53.105 --> 00:12:54.540
If he didn't think
he had the experience,

00:12:54.540 --> 00:12:55.474
he wouldn't have nominated.

00:12:55.474 --> 00:12:57.042
He said that that had been
one of the questions

00:12:57.042 --> 00:12:59.345
that people had posed about him.

00:12:59.345 --> 00:13:00.513
Obviously,
the President thought --

00:13:00.513 --> 00:13:02.081
The Press: So, he thinks Dr.
Jackson has all the experience

00:13:02.081 --> 00:13:03.582
necessary to run the department?

00:13:03.582 --> 00:13:06.318
Ms. Sanders:  Look, I think
he has an incredibly strong --

00:13:06.318 --> 00:13:07.386
The Press: It's a yes
or no question.

00:13:07.386 --> 00:13:09.855
Ms. Sanders: -- background.
He's a highly qualified,

00:13:09.855 --> 00:13:11.524
highly skilled individual.

00:13:11.524 --> 00:13:14.226
And if he didn't think he was
capable of doing the job,

00:13:14.226 --> 00:13:17.363
he wouldn't have announced his
nomination in the first place.

00:13:17.363 --> 00:13:18.898
The Press: Let me just
follow up, if I can.

00:13:18.898 --> 00:13:21.634
Just since you brought up
being taken out of context,

00:13:21.634 --> 00:13:23.769
if seems to be
a press-related question.

00:13:23.769 --> 00:13:26.205
Are you trying to say
that this administration

00:13:26.205 --> 00:13:28.207
is a champion of a free press?

00:13:28.207 --> 00:13:29.842
That seems --

00:13:29.842 --> 00:13:32.745
Ms. Sanders:  I certainly think
that, as I stated a moment ago,

00:13:32.745 --> 00:13:34.980
we support a free press

00:13:34.980 --> 00:13:36.749
but we also support
a fair press.

00:13:37.449 --> 00:13:40.319
And I think that those things
should go hand in hand,

00:13:40.319 --> 00:13:42.988
and there's a certain
responsibility by the press

00:13:42.988 --> 00:13:45.758
to report accurate information.
I think a number of people --

00:13:45.758 --> 00:13:46.659
The Press: Isn't there
a certain responsibility

00:13:46.659 --> 00:13:47.826
on the part of the President --

00:13:47.826 --> 00:13:49.495
Ms. Sanders:  I think a number
of people in this room

00:13:49.495 --> 00:13:50.729
do that every single day.

00:13:50.729 --> 00:13:52.631
They do their very best
to provide fair

00:13:52.631 --> 00:13:53.999
and accurate information.

00:13:53.999 --> 00:13:55.935
I certainly support that,
and that's one of the reasons

00:13:55.935 --> 00:13:57.803
I'm standing here
taking your questions --

00:13:57.803 --> 00:13:59.205
The Press: We appreciate that.

00:13:59.205 --> 00:14:01.073
Ms. Sanders:  -- and a lot
of times taking your questions

00:14:01.073 --> 00:14:04.009
in a tone that's completely
unnecessary, unneeded,

00:14:04.009 --> 00:14:06.512
and, frankly, doesn't help
further the conversation

00:14:06.512 --> 00:14:07.680
or help the American people

00:14:07.680 --> 00:14:10.049
get any more information
in a better way,

00:14:10.049 --> 00:14:11.584
which is your job and my job.

00:14:11.584 --> 00:14:12.585
And that's what
I'm trying to do.

00:14:12.585 --> 00:14:13.752
The Press: I fully appreciate
that. But, Sarah --

00:14:13.752 --> 00:14:14.954
Ms. Sanders: I'm going
to move on. David, go ahead.

00:14:14.954 --> 00:14:16.622
The Press: But the President's
tone towards the press --

00:14:16.622 --> 00:14:18.290
Ms. Sanders: Jim,
I'm finished here.

00:14:18.290 --> 00:14:19.825
The Press: The President's tone
towards the press is obviously

00:14:19.825 --> 00:14:20.926
not helpful at times --

00:14:20.926 --> 00:14:22.094
Ms. Sanders: Thank you, Jim.

00:14:22.094 --> 00:14:23.729
The Press: -- and I think
that that's plain to see.

00:14:23.729 --> 00:14:24.897
Ms. Sanders:  David.

00:14:24.897 --> 00:14:26.432
The Press: A Navy inspector
general had problems

00:14:26.432 --> 00:14:27.733
with the way Jackson
ran his medical office,

00:14:27.733 --> 00:14:29.301
which only has 50 people in it.

00:14:29.301 --> 00:14:31.036
What makes him qualified
to run a big department

00:14:31.036 --> 00:14:32.871
that has 350,000 people?

00:14:32.871 --> 00:14:35.708
Ms. Sanders:  Look, I saw
a number of members

00:14:35.708 --> 00:14:40.779
of both the House and Senate
do interviews today,

00:14:40.779 --> 00:14:42.815
just earlier this morning,
in which they said,

00:14:42.815 --> 00:14:44.617
look, we've tried this
a number of other ways

00:14:44.617 --> 00:14:47.453
with people who have run
massive organizations,

00:14:47.453 --> 00:14:48.854
and it hasn't worked
out very well.

00:14:49.655 --> 00:14:51.123
This is a different approach,

00:14:51.123 --> 00:14:53.158
but it certainly doesn't mean
it's a wrong approach

00:14:53.158 --> 00:14:54.893
or that he's not qualified.

00:14:54.893 --> 00:14:57.863
This is somebody who's been
on the battlefields,

00:14:57.863 --> 00:15:01.033
made decisions at
a very high-stress level,

00:15:01.033 --> 00:15:02.835
and saved a number
of individuals'

00:15:02.835 --> 00:15:05.471
lives in some of the most
trying circumstances.

00:15:05.471 --> 00:15:08.674
Somebody that understands the
relationship between veterans,

00:15:08.674 --> 00:15:09.642
and the needs and the care

00:15:09.642 --> 00:15:11.377
that they have
as a veteran himself --

00:15:11.377 --> 00:15:13.245
or as a service member himself,

00:15:13.245 --> 00:15:15.080
and somebody who has
a relationship

00:15:15.080 --> 00:15:16.482
and a deep-rooted care

00:15:16.482 --> 00:15:19.151
and concern for those
individuals that may be far

00:15:19.151 --> 00:15:22.221
and above what we've seen
from previous administrators

00:15:22.221 --> 00:15:23.922
that have overseen that agency.

00:15:23.922 --> 00:15:25.524
He's a highly
qualified individual,

00:15:25.524 --> 00:15:27.192
and we're going to
continue looking at this

00:15:27.192 --> 00:15:28.394
and continue
moving forward.

00:15:28.394 --> 00:15:30.763
Julie.

00:15:30.763 --> 00:15:32.464
The Press: Are you telling us
that the White House

00:15:32.464 --> 00:15:34.099
was not aware of
any of the allegations

00:15:34.099 --> 00:15:36.669
before the President
decided to name Dr. Jackson?

00:15:36.669 --> 00:15:38.037
Just, first of all, to clarify.

00:15:38.037 --> 00:15:39.638
Ms. Sanders: I'm telling you
that none of those things

00:15:39.638 --> 00:15:43.175
have come up in the four
separate background

00:15:43.175 --> 00:15:45.110
investigations
that have taken place.

00:15:45.110 --> 00:15:47.613
There's been no area of concern

00:15:47.613 --> 00:15:50.649
that was raised
for Dr. Jackson specifically.

00:15:51.283 --> 00:15:52.284
The Press: Can you describe
to us, then,

00:15:52.284 --> 00:15:54.153
what the vetting process
was at the White House

00:15:54.153 --> 00:15:55.454
before he was named,

00:15:55.454 --> 00:15:57.156
given that, as David
just mentioned,

00:15:57.156 --> 00:15:58.490
there is an inspector
general report

00:15:58.490 --> 00:16:00.526
and there have been
allegations in the past

00:16:00.526 --> 00:16:01.527
that are now coming to light,

00:16:01.527 --> 00:16:03.962
but they existed before
the President chose him?

00:16:03.962 --> 00:16:06.532
Ms. Sanders:  Again, Dr. Jackson
has undergone

00:16:06.532 --> 00:16:10.336
four separate background checks.

00:16:10.336 --> 00:16:12.471
One that was
conducted by the FBI,

00:16:12.471 --> 00:16:15.240
and all those revealed
nothing and came back

00:16:15.240 --> 00:16:18.811
with a clean recommendation.

00:16:18.811 --> 00:16:20.379
The Press: So, the only vetting
that was done of him

00:16:20.379 --> 00:16:21.613
as a nominee was to look

00:16:21.613 --> 00:16:23.882
at his past background checks,
is what you're telling us?

00:16:23.882 --> 00:16:25.117
Ms. Sanders: No -- I mean,
there's a number of things.

00:16:25.117 --> 00:16:27.052
But you also have to remember
this is somebody

00:16:27.052 --> 00:16:29.588
that spends more time
with the President

00:16:29.588 --> 00:16:30.956
than just about anyone.

00:16:31.690 --> 00:16:34.426
These investigations
are very thorough

00:16:35.361 --> 00:16:37.996
and certainly something that
was taken into consideration.

00:16:37.996 --> 00:16:38.964
Blake.

00:16:38.964 --> 00:16:40.099
The Press: Sarah, thank you.

00:16:40.099 --> 00:16:41.266
Let me ask you
a couple questions

00:16:41.266 --> 00:16:42.434
about the Tim Cook meeting

00:16:42.434 --> 00:16:44.236
that is either wrapped
or going on right now.

00:16:44.236 --> 00:16:45.437
Do you, by chance,
have a readout

00:16:45.437 --> 00:16:47.973
of what exactly took place?
Did the President promise to --

00:16:47.973 --> 00:16:49.575
Ms. Sanders:  The meeting
was still ongoing

00:16:49.575 --> 00:16:50.809
when the briefing started.

00:16:50.809 --> 00:16:54.380
I know that the primary focus
and purpose of the meeting

00:16:54.380 --> 00:16:55.914
is to discuss trade.

00:16:55.914 --> 00:16:58.250
It's something that's been
on the President's schedule

00:16:58.250 --> 00:16:59.385
for the last couple of weeks.

00:16:59.385 --> 00:17:01.286
If we have any additional
information, we'll let you know.

00:17:01.286 --> 00:17:03.155
The Press: Let me ask you.
In the last month now,

00:17:03.155 --> 00:17:05.457
the President has met
with Bill Gates,

00:17:05.457 --> 00:17:08.160
who is the second-wealthiest
individual in the world.

00:17:08.160 --> 00:17:09.361
Now he's meeting with Tim Cook,

00:17:09.361 --> 00:17:13.665
who runs the largest company
in the United States.

00:17:13.665 --> 00:17:16.769
Does the President have
any intentions, at any point,

00:17:16.769 --> 00:17:19.304
to meet with the wealthiest
individual in the world,

00:17:19.304 --> 00:17:20.539
Jeff Bezos?

00:17:20.539 --> 00:17:24.176
And if so, under what
conditions would that be?

00:17:24.176 --> 00:17:26.245
Ms. Sanders: I'm not aware
of that being on the schedule.

00:17:26.245 --> 00:17:29.715
I certainly haven't seen it
on any of the look-aheads.

00:17:30.783 --> 00:17:32.651
I think the President
would be open to it,

00:17:32.651 --> 00:17:35.120
but I'm not aware of anything
being locked in at this point.

00:17:35.120 --> 00:17:36.355
Ashley.

00:17:36.355 --> 00:17:39.124
The Press: Sarah, Scott Pruitt
lived for below-market rent

00:17:39.124 --> 00:17:40.426
in a Capitol Hill row house

00:17:40.426 --> 00:17:42.694
owned by an energy
industry lobbyist.

00:17:42.694 --> 00:17:45.998
He reportedly directed staff
to give raises to top aides,

00:17:45.998 --> 00:17:47.833
and then obfuscated about it.

00:17:47.833 --> 00:17:51.370
He spent over $150,000
of taxpayer dollars

00:17:51.370 --> 00:17:53.439
on first-class travel.

00:17:53.439 --> 00:17:55.073
And he reportedly
once even tried

00:17:55.073 --> 00:17:57.910
to get his security detail
to use their sirens,

00:17:57.910 --> 00:18:00.913
so he could get to
a reservation at Le Diplomate,

00:18:01.647 --> 00:18:03.816
among other alleged
ethical lapses.

00:18:03.816 --> 00:18:05.984
I know you've said yesterday
you were looking at reports

00:18:05.984 --> 00:18:07.586
about him,
but can you sort of explain

00:18:08.120 --> 00:18:09.488
why he still has a job

00:18:09.488 --> 00:18:10.789
in the President's Cabinet,

00:18:10.789 --> 00:18:15.194
and also how his behavior
is in keeping with the values

00:18:15.194 --> 00:18:16.495
of draining the swamp?

00:18:16.495 --> 00:18:19.198
Ms. Sanders: Again,
we're evaluating these concerns,

00:18:19.198 --> 00:18:21.300
and we expect
the EPA Administrator

00:18:21.300 --> 00:18:22.201
to answer for them,

00:18:22.201 --> 00:18:23.635
and we'll keep you posted.

00:18:23.635 --> 00:18:24.770
Ayesha.

00:18:24.770 --> 00:18:26.338
The Press: Thanks.
Just to follow up on that --

00:18:26.338 --> 00:18:29.575
when you say you expect
Administrator Pruitt

00:18:29.575 --> 00:18:32.344
to answer for these accusations,

00:18:32.344 --> 00:18:34.246
where do you expect
that to happen?

00:18:34.246 --> 00:18:36.615
Like, are you looking
for this in hearings?

00:18:37.216 --> 00:18:38.650
Is the White House
asking questions?

00:18:38.650 --> 00:18:40.285
Ms. Sanders: We're having
ongoing conversations.

00:18:40.953 --> 00:18:44.389
The Press: And also, just to
follow up on Jackson.

00:18:45.123 --> 00:18:48.927
When you say that he's been
through four background checks,

00:18:48.927 --> 00:18:51.997
can you say -- but these
allegations have now come up,

00:18:51.997 --> 00:18:53.665
and some of them
are very serious --

00:18:53.665 --> 00:18:56.335
is the White House going to
look into the allegations

00:18:56.335 --> 00:18:58.003
that have been made against him

00:18:58.003 --> 00:19:00.072
about drinking on the job
and (inaudible)?

00:19:00.072 --> 00:19:01.340
Ms. Sanders: Certainly,
something that we

00:19:01.340 --> 00:19:02.841
would look at, absolutely.

00:19:02.841 --> 00:19:04.543
I'll take one last question.

00:19:04.543 --> 00:19:05.711
Francesca.

00:19:05.711 --> 00:19:07.779
The Press: Thank you, Sarah.
I wanted to clarify, too,

00:19:07.779 --> 00:19:09.548
about these four
background checks.

00:19:09.548 --> 00:19:11.483
Were any of these
background checks

00:19:11.483 --> 00:19:13.352
since President Trump
took office

00:19:13.352 --> 00:19:17.523
or since he was named
as the nominee for VA Secretary?

00:19:17.523 --> 00:19:18.757
And has the White House

00:19:18.757 --> 00:19:21.493
ever been informed
of allegations

00:19:21.493 --> 00:19:23.829
like these -- like excessively
drinking on the job

00:19:23.829 --> 00:19:27.232
or passing out medication
like candy, as it were --

00:19:27.232 --> 00:19:30.702
since he was the physician
for President Trump?

00:19:30.702 --> 00:19:32.671
Ms. Sanders: I'm not aware
of any of those allegations

00:19:32.671 --> 00:19:35.807
being made until
the nomination was made.

00:19:36.408 --> 00:19:38.377
The Press: And to follow up
on what I was asking

00:19:38.377 --> 00:19:40.145
about the background check.

00:19:40.145 --> 00:19:42.814
When was his most recent
background check?

00:19:42.814 --> 00:19:44.750
Ms. Sanders: I'd have to look
at the specific date,

00:19:44.750 --> 00:19:47.119
but my understanding
is that a new one took place

00:19:47.119 --> 00:19:49.154
at the time of
the new administration.

00:19:49.154 --> 00:19:50.689
Thanks, so much, guys,
see you tomorrow.

